# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acetaldehyde
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acetaldehyde/5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine] The conversion is an example of a structurally complex compound efficiently made from simple precursors.
[src:acetaldehyde/5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine] Under related conditions, the condensation of acetaldehyde and ammonia delivers 2-picoline.
[src:acetaldehyde/5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine] Oxidation of 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine with nitric acid gives nicotinic acid via the decarboxylation of 2,5-pyridinedicarboxylic acid.
[src:acetaldehyde/5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine] Like most alkylpyridines, the LD50 of 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine is modest, being 368 mg/kg (oral, rat).
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:acetaldehyde/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] In organic chemistry, an **acetal** is a functional group with the connectivity R2C(OR')2.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Here, the R groups can be organic fragments (a carbon atom, with arbitrary other atoms attached to that) or hydrogen, while the R' groups must be organic fragments, not hydrogen.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] The two R' groups can be equivalent to each other (a "symmetric acetal") or not (a "mixed acetal").
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] An acetal is formed from and convertible to two alcohol molecules and an aldehyde or ketone, but acetals have substantially different chemical stability and reactivity as compared to the analogous carbonyl compounds.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] The central carbon atom has four bonds to it, and is therefore saturated and has tetrahedral geometry.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] The IUPAC originally deprecated the usage of the word ketal altogether, but has since reversed its decision.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] However, in contrast to historical usage, ketals are now a subset of acetals, a term that now encompasses both aldehyde- and ketone-derived structures.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] If one of the R groups has an oxygen as the first atom (that is, there are more than two oxygens single-bonded to the central carbon), the functional group is instead an orthoester.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] In contrast to variations of R, both R' groups are organic fragments.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] If one R' is a hydrogen, the functional group is instead a hemiacetal, while if both are H, the functional group is a ketone hydrate or aldehyde hydrate.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Formation of an acetal occurs when the hydroxyl group of a hemiacetal becomes protonated and is lost as water.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] The carbocation that is produced is then rapidly attacked by a molecule of alcohol.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Loss of the proton from the attached alcohol gives the acetal.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Acetals are stable compared to hemiacetals but their formation is a reversible equilibrium as with esters.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] As a reaction to create an acetal proceeds, water must be removed from the reaction mixture, for example, with a Dean–Stark apparatus, lest it hydrolyse the product back to the hemiacetal.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] The formation of acetals reduces the total number of molecules present (carbonyl + 2 alcohol → acetal + water) and therefore is generally not favourable with regard to entropy.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] One situation where the reaction is not entropically unfavourable is when a single diol molecule is used rather than two separate alcohol molecules (carbonyl + diol → acetal + water).
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Acetalization and ketalization are the organic reactions that involve the formation of an acetal (or ketals) from aldehydes and ketones, respectively.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Since each step is often a rapid equilibrium, the reaction must be driven by removal of water.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Methods for removing water include azeotropic distillation and trapping water with desiccants like aluminium oxide and molecular sieves.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Steps assumed to be involved: protonation of the carbonyl oxygen, addition of the alcohol to the protonated carbonyl, protonolysis of the resulting hemiacetal or hemiketal, and addition of the second alcohol.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Another way to avoid the entropic cost is to perform the synthesis by acetal exchange (**transacetalization**), using a pre-existing acetal-type reagent as the OR'-group donor rather than simple addition of alcohols themselves.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] One type of reagent used for this method is an orthoester.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] In this case, water produced along with the acetal product is destroyed when it hydrolyses residual orthoester molecules, and this side reaction also produces more alcohol to be used in the main reaction.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Since many sugars are polyhydroxy aldehydes and ketones, sugars are a rich source of acetals and ketals.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Most glycosidic bonds in carbohydrates and other polysaccharides are acetal linkages.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Cellulose is a ubiquitous example of a polyacetal.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Benzylidene acetal and acetonide as protecting groups used in research of modified sugars.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Acetals also find application as chiral auxiliaries.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Indeed acetals of chiral glycols like, e.g. derivatives of tartaric acid can be asymmetrically opened with high selectivity.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] This enables the construction of new chiral centers.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Formaldehyde forms a rich collection of acetals.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] This tendency reflects the fact that low molecular weight aldehydes are prone to self-condensation such that the C=O bond is replaced by an acetal.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] The acetal formed from formaldehyde (two hydrogens attached to the central carbon) is sometimes called a *formal* or the methylenedioxy group.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] The acetal formed from acetone is sometimes called an acetonide.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Formaldehyde forms paraformaldehyde and 1,3,5-trioxane.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Polyoxymethylene (POM) plastic, also known as "acetal" or "polyacetal", is a polyacetal (and a polyether), and a polymer of formaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Acetaldehyde converts to paraldehyde and metaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Phenylsulfonylethylidene (PSE) acetal is an example of arylsulfonyl acetal possessing atypical properties, like resistance to acid hydrolysis which leads to selective introduction and removal of the protective group.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] 1,1-Diethoxyethane (acetaldehyde diethyl acetal), sometimes called simply "acetal", is an important flavouring compound in distilled beverages.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Two ketals of ethyl acetoacetate are used in commercial fragrances.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Fructone (CH3C(O2C2H4)CH2CO2C2H5), an ethylene glycol ketal, and fraistone (CH3C(O2C2H3CH3)CH2CO2C2H5), a propylene glycol ketal, are commercial fragrances.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] Used in a more general sense, the term **X**,**Y**-*acetal* also refers to any functional group that consists of a carbon bearing two heteroatoms **X** and **Y**.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetal] For example, *N*,*O*-acetal refers to compounds of type R1R2C(OR)(NR'2) (R,R' ≠ H) also known as a *hemiaminal ether* or aminal, a.k.a. aminoacetal.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-data-page] This page provides supplementary chemical data on acetaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-data-page] The handling of this chemical may require safety precautions.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-data-page] The directions on the Material Safety Datasheet (MSDS) should be followed.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-data-page] Table data obtained from *CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics* 44th ed.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-dehydrogenase] (Acetylating) **Acetaldehyde dehydrogenases** are a class of enzymes found in bacteria.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-dehydrogenase] Acetylating acetaldehyde dehydrogenases (EC 1.2.1.10) are dehydrogenase enzymes which catalyze the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetyl-CoA, or the reverse.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-dehydrogenase] This enzyme is part of ethanol fermentation in certain species, and in particular the conversion of pyruvate to ethanol.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-dehydrogenase] This three step pathway starts by converting pyruvate to Acetyl-CoA, then uses this enzyme to produce acetaldehyde, and finally uses an alcohol dehydrogenase to convert acetaldehyde to ethanol.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-dehydrogenase] This is the most widespread approach in bacteria, but a different 2 step pathway that uses pyruvate decarboxylase is more common in yeast.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-dehydrogenase] In bacteria, acylating acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms a bifunctional heterodimer with metal-dependent 4-hydroxy-2-ketovalerate aldolase.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde-dehydrogenase] Such communication between proteins allows for the efficient transfer substrates from one active site to the next.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:acetaldehyde/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:acetaldehyde/adh1c] This gene encodes class I alcohol dehydrogenase, gamma subunit, which is a member of the alcohol dehydrogenase family.
[src:acetaldehyde/adh1c] Members of this enzyme family metabolize a wide variety of substrates, including ethanol (beverage alcohol), retinol, other aliphatic alcohols, hydroxysteroids, and lipid peroxidation products.
[src:acetaldehyde/adh1c] Class I alcohol dehydrogenase, consisting of several homo- and heterodimers of alpha, beta, and gamma subunits, exhibit high activity for ethanol oxidation and play a major role in ethanol catabolism.
[src:acetaldehyde/adh1c] Three genes encoding alpha, beta and gamma subunits are tandemly organized in a genomic segment as a gene cluster.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Most White people have both major isozymes, while approximately 36% of East Asians have the cytosolic isozyme but not a functional mitochondrial isozyme.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] A remarkably higher frequency of acute alcohol intoxication among East Asians than among Whites could be related to this absence of a catalytically active form of ALDH2.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The increased exposure to acetaldehyde in individuals with the catalytically inactive form may also confer greater susceptibility to many types of cancer.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The *ALDH2* gene is about 44 kbp in length and contains at least 13 exons which encode 517 amino acid residues.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Except for the signal NH2-terminal peptide, which is absent in the mature enzyme, the amino acid sequence deduced from the exons coincided with the reported primary structure of human liver ALDH2.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Several introns contain Alu repetitive sequences.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] A TATA-like sequence (TTATAAAA) and a CAAT-like sequence (GTCATCAT) are located 473 and 515 bp, respectively, upstream from the translation initiation codon.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] ALDH2 is a tetrameric enzyme that contains three domains; two dinucleotide-binding domains and a three-stranded beta-sheet domain.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The active site of ALDH2 is divided into two halves by the nicotinamide ring of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+).
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Adjacent to the A-side (Pro-R) of the nicotinamide ring is a cluster of three cysteines (Cys301, Cys302 and Cys303) and adjacent to the B-side (Pro-S) are Thr244, Glu268, Glu476 and an ordered water molecule bound to Thr244 and Glu476.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Although there is a recognizable Rossmann fold, the coenzyme-binding region of ALDH2 binds NAD+ in a manner not seen in other NAD+-binding enzymes.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The positions of the residues near the nicotinamide ring of NAD+ suggest a chemical mechanism whereby Glu268 functions as a general base through a bound water molecule.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The sidechain amide nitrogen of Asn169 and the peptide nitrogen of Cys302 are in position to stabilize the oxyanion present in the tetrahedral transition state prior to hydride transfer.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The functional importance of residue Glu487 now appears to be due to indirect interactions of this residue with the substrate-binding site via Arg264 and Arg475.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Mitochondrial aldehyde dehydrogenase belongs to the aldehyde dehydrogenase family of enzymes that catalyze the chemical transformation from acetaldehyde to acetic acid.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Aldehyde dehydrogenase is the second enzyme of the major oxidative pathway of alcohol metabolism.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Human ALDH2 is especially efficient on acetaldehyde compared to ALDH1.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Additionally, ALDH2 functions as a protector against oxidative stress.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The inactivating ALDH2*2 mutation is "the most common single point mutation in humans".
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] This mutation is found in very few White people, but about 50% of East Asians are heterozygous for this mutation.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The ALDH2*2 allele encodes lysine instead of glutamic acid at amino acid 487, distorting the NAD+ binding site.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] ALDH2 assembles and functions as a tetramer and requires all four of its components to be active in order to metabolize acetaldehyde.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] People heterozygous for ALDH2*2 have only 10% to 45% enzyme activity, while those homozygous for ALDH2*2 have as little as 1% to 5% remaining activity.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The lack of ALDH2 activity has a number of consequences, detailed in section § Inhibition and genetic deficiency below.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] In the overall Japanese population, about 57% of individuals are homozygous for the normal allele, 40% are heterozygous for the ALDH2*2 allele, and 3% are homozygous for the ALDH2*2 allele.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The best-known consequence of ALDH2 dysfunction is in relation to the consumption of ethanol.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] People heterozygous or homozygous for the ALDH2*2 metabolize ethanol to acetaldehyde normally but metabolize acetaldehyde poorly.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] As a result, they accumulate increased levels of acetaldehyde after consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Effects include facial flushing (i.e. the "alcohol flush reaction"), urticaria, systemic dermatitis, and alcohol-induced respiratory reactions such as rhinitis and the exacerbation of asthma bronchoconstriction.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] People with a genetic ALDH2*2 deficiency have historically had a lower likelihood of developing alcoholism, both from stronger adverse effects and a possible reduction of dopamine release.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] However, this effect is not absolute: during the 1980s, there has been a steady increase in the number of Japanese alcoholics who carry the ALDH2*2 mutation.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] A strong social pressure to drink have overcome this genetic barrier to alcoholism.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] Disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2 and causes a similar effect, has been used as an alcohol-quitting aid.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] More recently, ALDH2 has been implicated in a number of pathways beyond alcohol metabolism.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] ALDH2 dysfunction is supposedly associated with a variety of human diseases including diabetes, neurodegenerative diseases, cardiovascular diseases and stroke, cancer, Fanconi anemia, pain, osteoporosis, and the process of aging.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] A case-control study in a Japanese population showed that deficiency of ALDH2 activity influences the risk for late-onset Alzheimer's disease.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] The ALDH2 knockout mice display age-related memory deficits in various tasks, as well as endothelial dysfunction, brain atrophy, and other Alzheimer's disease-associated pathologies, including marked increases in lipid peroxidation products, amyloid-beta, p-tau and activated caspases.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] These behavioral and biochemical Alzheimer's disease-like deficits were efficiently ameliorated when these mice were treated with isotope-reinforced lipids (deuterated polyunsaturated fatty acids).
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] An activator of ALDH2 enzymatic activity, Alda-1 (N-(1,3-benzodioxol-5-ylmethyl)-2,6-dichlorobenzamide), has been shown to reduce ischemia-induced cardiac damage caused by myocardial infarction.
[src:acetaldehyde/aldh2] ALDH2 has been shown to interact with GroEL.
